data.name: Van Halen "Jump" Music Video
data.description:
Video support for a live performance of "Jump" by Van Halen at Church by the Glades.

Shot on RED

The underwater portion of the video was shot on a RED One in an AquaVideo underwater housing.  This portion took around 6 hours of non-stop filming underwater with the various musicians.  All of the instruments were cheap props and were either donated or purchased used for the sole purpose of this video shoot.  Obviously after 6 hours underwater everything ended up quite ruined.

Lead singer: Justin Thomas
Electric Guitar: David Rodriguez
Keys: Ariel Medina
Drums: Sam Diapen
Bass: Rob Lopez

data.name: Dead and Gone
data.description:
Video accompanying live performance of the song "Dead and Gone" at Church by the Glades.

Created entirely in After Effects.  Both singers were shot on a blue screen and keyed/rotoscoped out.  Paint splatters were then hand-tracked onto their bodies.  Not including shooting and prep, the final video took around 60 hours to make and the final After Effects project file totaled over 800 layers.

Typography utilizes the creatively-made Toyota iQ font as seen here: http://www.vimeo.com/5233789

WINNER: Dirt 2009 Dirties "Best In-Service Video Element"

embed.html: <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/6857204?badge=0&autopause=0&player_id=0" width="1280" height="720" frameborder="0" title="Dead and Gone" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>

data.name: RED Test #1: Band Rehearsal
data.description:
Shot on a RED One camera with a Nikon mount and Sigma 18-50mm f2.8-4.5 lens.  We're still awaiting the arrival of our Red Pro Prime lenses, but until then I'm trying to get used to shooting RED.

All footage here is directly off the camera imported through Final Cut Pro with no colour correcting or any touching up.  Our RED is running build 16.

Please ignore some of the poor camera work as I am getting used to the shoulder mount and some shots may look a little rough.

Overall I'm very pleased with what has come directly off the camera.  Even with a lens that isn't the most expensive glass out there I still was able to get some decent footage.

embed.html: <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/6138558?badge=0&autopause=0&player_id=0" width="1280" height="640" frameborder="0" title="RED Test #1: Band Rehearsal" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>

data.name: Lasting Joy vs. Circumstantial Happiness
data.description:
This piece was used as an intro to our First Wednesday service on Joy.  The purpose was to contrast the difference between true Joy and circumstantial Happiness.  We chose an abstract visual story line to go along with a moving script written by Kristin Baker.

Everything was shot on a Panasonic HVX-200 with a Brevis lens adapter system for the cinematic look.  Some post processing was done in Final Cut Pro and After Effects.

[Song Used: "Your Hand in Mine" by Explosions in the Sky.  Shown Nov 5, 2008 at Granger Community Church, "First Wednesday: Joy"]

data.name: That's My King!
data.description:
Visuals set to the audio of the famous sermon "Seven Way King" as spoken by Dr. S.M. Lockridge.  The audio is slightly edited for a better flow in the video.

The music in the background was performed live by the GCC band while the video played on the screens.  It then led directly into the worship song "Here is Our King"  (To see the performance in it's entirety go here: http://www.gccwired.com/mediaplayer/playeropener.asp?id=478 )

Created entirely using After Effects with footage from the movie "The Passion of the Christ".  The video took 30 hours to create plus around 6 hours of rendering.  The final After Effects project file totaled well over 600 layers.

By popular demand I have enabled downloading of this video.  This is for personal, non-commercial use only.  Please contact me before using for any other means.  If you would like to download this video without the live band underneath, that version can be found here: http://vimeo.com/10485795

embed.html: <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/1371841?badge=0&autopause=0&player_id=0" width="1280" height="720" frameborder="0" title="That's My King!" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>

data.name: "Heroes" Series Trailer
data.description:
A trailer for the "Heroes" series at Granger Community Church, focusing on finding your fit in serving.

Created entirely in After Effects.  A 2D satellite image of the earth was turned into a photo collage using the faces of volunteers around church courtesy of David Harris (another volunteer) Using After Effects, this was turned into a 3D globe hovering in the vastness of space with the familiar Heroes eclipse.

Took an entire week to create and another 12 hours of the computer crunching just to render it out.
